<p>
	The 
	<em>
		tandas
	</em>
	were nicely grouped in sets of four songs each, separated by a 
	<em>
		cortina
	</em>
	that was longer than we tend to have in the States. Nobody left the dance floor before the tanda was complete, but instead danced to every song once on the floor.
</p>
<p>
	Most couples spent the first thirty seconds or so of each song talking to each other; the only people who charged right into dancing at the beginning of each song were, well, us Type-A tourists, trying, I guess, to maximize every minute of milonga on our visit. I'd heard about this Argentine practice of waiting for the song to develop before dancing, and I've always loved the concept. To be in a place where it's considered normal, even mandatory, is a real pleasure. 
</p>
<h2 class="tips">
	Tips
</h2>
<ul>
	<li>
		<p>
			Seriously, just hang out for the first verse of the song. Listen to the music. Relax. If you're the leader, then start dancing when you see the guy behind your partner start dancing.
		</p>
	</li>
</ul>
